
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `dbus-monitor` baraye didan va zabt kardane peygham haye DBus (Desktop Bus) be kar mirevad. DBus yek system baraye ertebat bein process-ha dar Linux va system-haye amale digar ast. In dastoor be shoma komak mikonad ta bebini che process-ha’ee ba ham sohbat mikonand va che etela’ati mobadele mishavad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `--system` --> 🖥️ Peygham haye system-wide DBus ra monitor mikonad.
    🔹 `--session` --> 👤 Peygham haye session-specific DBus ra monitor mikonad (default).
    🔹 `--profile` --> ⏱️ Baz kardane yek profile baraye analysis behtare performance.
    🔹 `--address ADDRESS` --> 📍 Montor kardane yek address DBus khass.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ dbus-monitor

    🔹 Monitor kardane hameye peygham haye DBus dar session-e shakhsi.

    $ dbus-monitor --system

    🔹 Monitor kardane hameye peygham haye DBus dar system.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ dbus-monitor | grep "org.kde.screensaver"

    🔹 Monitor kardane hameye peygham hayi ke shamel "org.kde.screensaver" hastand, ke be shoma komak mikonad bebini screensaver che joor kar mikonad.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `dbus-monitor` command is used to observe and record D-Bus (Desktop Bus) messages. D-Bus is a system for inter-process communication on Linux and other operating systems.  This command helps you see which processes are communicating with each other and what information is being exchanged.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `--system` --> 🖥️ Monitor system-wide D-Bus messages.
    🔹 `--session` --> 👤 Monitor session-specific D-Bus messages (default).
    🔹 `--profile` --> ⏱️ Open a profile for better performance analysis.
    🔹 `--address ADDRESS` --> 📍 Monitor a specific D-Bus address.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ dbus-monitor

    🔹 Monitor all D-Bus messages in your personal session.

    $ dbus-monitor --system

    🔹 Monitor all D-Bus messages on the system.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ dbus-monitor | grep "org.kde.screensaver"

    🔹 Monitor all messages that include "org.kde.screensaver," which helps you see how the screensaver is working.
